INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (40,1,'2012-08-31 21:24:50','2012-08-31 21:24:50','<strong>Penn State University\'s general liability insurer, PMA, is attempting to avoid picking up the tab for expenses related to the civil suits filed by two of Jerry Sandusky\'s victims.  This could result in Penn State paying out-of-pocket the entire amount of civil damages and costs related to the current and future sex abuse lawsuits.  </strong><!--more-->\r\n\r\nOn July 29, 2012, Penn State President Rodney Erickson appeared on CBS\'s Face the Nation where he stated, \"We have, like any university of our size... general liability coverage and we believe that that we are adequately covered. In addition to that we hope to be able to settle as many of these cases as quickly as possible.\"  If PMA is successful in its current action, Penn State will no longer have the adequate coverage Mr. Erickson spoke of.  Rather, Penn State will be left to pay the staggering amount of any settlements or damages that will arise from these civil suits.\r\n\r\nPMA filed a motion arguing that coverage should be denied because the Penn State administration failed to disclose what it knew about former coach Jerry Sandusky\'s behavior (see the story here <a href=\"http://www.cnn.com/2012/07/25/us/pennsylvania-penn-state-insurer/index.html?hpt=ju_bn3\">http://www.cnn.com/2012/07/25/us/pennsylvania-penn-state-insurer/index.html?hpt=ju_bn3</a>).  PMA argues in the motion that, \"It would be unlawful and contradictory to public policy to require PMA to provide coverage to PSU under any policy issued to PSU after May 1998 with respect to PSU\'s concealment of Sandusky\'s sexually abusive conduct ... and failure to take appropriate action to prevent Sandusky from molesting minors.\"\r\n\r\nGenerally speaking, an insurer would have a duty to defend the insured for liability covered under the policy.  For example, most homeowner\'s insurance policies provide liability coverage for accidents such as a person falling on the property.  After the insured paid the deductible, the insurance company would pay any damages owed to the person who fell as well as other costs associated with litigation, up to the policy limit.\r\n\r\nOn a basic level, PMA\'s legal argument is that the insurance policy, as of May 1998, should be void due to Penn State failing to report potential liability.  The Penn State administration was aware of at least one potential sexual abuse lawsuit in 1998.  By failing to disclose this to PMA, the risk could not be evaluated in writing the insurance policy.  To put it simply, if PMA had been notified of the potential lawsuits, PMA may have decided to drop coverage or at least write a policy with a higher premium.  PMA could also have taken steps to limit liability exposure at that time.\r\n\r\nThis issue boils down to one primary question - should the insurance company be relieved of its obligation to defend its insured?  It is well established in Pennsylvania that an insured will not be able to recover from the insurance company when the insured misrepresented material facts on an insurance application, or during an insurance company\'s investigation into a claim.  However, in this instance Penn State did neither.\r\n\r\nPMA provided insurance to Penn State for several years prior to the Sandusky abuses began.  Therefore, Penn State presumably did not hide the allegations in an application.  Furthermore, PMA is not asserting that Penn State misrepresented any facts during PMA\'s current investigation or proceedings.  Thus, unless another exclusion or condition is written into the policy, PMA should be obligated to honor Penn State\'s insurance policy.\r\n\r\nThe problem for Penn State is that the discussion does not end there.  There may be other exclusions in the policy that could allow PMA to avoid coverage.  For instance, many policies contain a condition precedent for coverage requiring the insured to report claims, or potential claims, when the insured learns of the claim.  Clearly Penn State did not do that.  Unfortunately for Penn State, these exclusions are fairly common, and if that is the case, PMA might be able to run out on this tab leaving Penn State to pay millions of dollars in liability exposure.','Insurance Company Denying Liability Coverage to Penn State','','publish','open','open','','insurance-company-denying-liability-coverage-to-penn-state','','','2013-07-13 01:28:42','2013-07-13 01:28:42','',0,'http://myvaccineattorney.com/blog/?p=40',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (41,1,'2012-08-31 20:37:26','2012-08-31 20:37:26','<strong>Penn State University\'s general liability insurer, PMA, is not picking up the tab for expenses related to the civil suits filed by Jerry Sandusky\'s victims.  This could result in Penn State paying the entire amount of damages, as well as all litigation costs, out of pocket.  </strong>\n\n<strong></strong>PMA filed a motion arguing that coverage should be denied because the Penn State administration failed to disclose what it knew about former coach Jerry Sandusky\'s behavior (see the story here <a href=\"http://www.cnn.com/2012/07/25/us/pennsylvania-penn-state-insurer/index.html?hpt=ju_bn3\">http://www.cnn.com/2012/07/25/us/pennsylvania-penn-state-insurer/index.html?hpt=ju_bn3</a>).\n\nGenerally speaking, an insurer would have a duty to defend the insured for liability covered under the policy.  For example, most homeowner\'s insurance policies provide liability coverage for accidents such as a person falling on the property.  After the insured paid the deductible, the insurance company would pay any damages owed to the person who fell as well as other costs associated with litigation, up to the policy limit.\n\nPMA argues in the motion that, \"It would be unlawful and contradictory to public policy to require PMA to provide coverage to PSU under any policy issued to PSU after May 1998 with respect to PSU\'s concealment of Sandusky\'s sexually abusive conduct ... and failure to take appropriate action to prevent Sandusky from molesting minors.\"\n\nDespite the \"against public policy\" language, PMA\'s legal argument should be that the insurance policy, starting in May of 1998, was written on false pretenses.  The Penn State administration was aware of at least one potential sexual abuse lawsuit in 1998.  By failing to disclose this to PMA, the risk could not be evaluated in writing the insurance policy.  To put it simply, if PMA had been notified of the potential lawsuits, PMA may have decided to drop coverage or at least write a policy with a higher premium.  PMA could also have taken steps to limit liability exposure at that time.\n\nThis issue boils down to one primary question - should the insurance company be relieved of its obligations to provide the service they are paid to provide?  It is well established that an insured will not be able to recover from the insurance company when the insured misrepresented material facts on an insurance application, or during an insurance company\'s investigation into a claim.  However, in this instance Penn State did neither.\n\nPMA provided insurance to Penn State for several years prior to the Sandusky abuses began.  Therefore, Penn State presumably did not hide the allegations in an application.  Furthermore, none of the abuse victims filed civil lawsuits until this year.  PMA is not asserting that Penn State misrepresented any facts during current investigations or proceedings.  Thus, unless another exclusion or condition is written into the policy, PMA should obligated to honor Penn State\'s insurance policy.\n\nThere may be other exclusions in the policy that could allow PMA to escape these proceedings.  For instance, many policies contain a condition precedent for coverage requiring the insured to report claims, or potential claims, when the insured learns of the claim.  However, at this juncture it appears PMA may simply be piling on Penn State by citing \"public policy\" as a means for running out and leaving Penn State to pick up the tab.   Penn State\'s handling of the scandal was inept on so many levels.  Yet, this is not grounds for nullifying an insurance policy.','Insurance Company Denying Liability Coverage to Penn State','','inherit','open','open','','40-revision','','','2012-08-31 20:37:26','2012-08-31 20:37:26','',40,'http://myvaccineattorney.com/blog/?p=41',0,'revision','',0);
