INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (87,1,'2013-04-16 18:09:27','2013-04-16 18:09:27','The Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (VAERS) is a program created and administered by the Center for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and the Food and Drug Administration (FDA).  VAERS is a program used to track adverse reactions to vaccines.  VAERS allows the public to see this information about vaccine-related injuries and reactions.<!--more-->\r\n\r\nThe National Childhood Vaccine Injury Act (NCVIA) of 1986 requires vaccine manufacturers and healthcare providers to report any adverse reactions to vaccines.  However, anyone can file a VAERS report, including someone who receives a vaccine and has an adverse reaction.\r\n\r\nWe recommend that if you or your children have suffered an adverse reaction to a vaccine that you do file a VAERS Report.  These reports help the Department of Health and Human Services and the Center for Disease Control and Prevention to monitor illness and injury caused by vaccines, and prevent such adverse vaccine reactions in the future.  All VAERS reports are confidential, and all individual identifiers are removed from the data posted on the VAERS website.\r\n\r\nIf you wish to report an adverse event to a vaccine to VAERS, there are three ways to do so:\r\n\r\nOnline – Proceed to this link and follow the directions:  <a href=\"https://vaers.hhs.gov/esub/step1\">https://vaers.hhs.gov/esub/step1</a>\r\n\r\nFax – Download the VAERS Form from vaers.hhs.gov.  Complete the form and fax to (877) 721-0366.\r\n\r\nMail – Download the VAERS form from vaers.hhs.gov.  Mail the completed form to:\r\n\r\nVAERS\r\n\r\nPO Box 1100\r\n\r\nRockville, MD 20849-1100.\r\n\r\nFor more information regarding VAERS, please see their website at <a href=\"http://vaers.hhs.gov/index\">http://vaers.hhs.gov/index</a>.  For more information regarding vaccine injury claims, please contact the law firm of Muller Brazil LLP for a free consultation.','Reporting Adverse Vaccine Reactions ','','publish','open','open','','reporting-adverse-vaccine-reactions','','','2013-07-13 01:24:29','2013-07-13 01:24:29','',0,'http://myvaccineattorney.com/blog/?p=87',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (89,1,'2013-05-07 19:33:54','2013-05-07 19:33:54','Can my employer make me get a flu shot?\r\n\r\nThe issue of <strong>vaccine injuries</strong> has left both employers and employees with a question that may not have a definite answer. With the beginning of each flu season, both employers and employees may wonder if an employer can legally mandate an employee to get a flu shot in order to maintain employment with the company. Clearly, the flu can knock out a large percentage of an entire workforce, severely hampering productivity and day to day operations. So, is it legal for a business owner to adopt a mandatory flu shot policy?<!--more-->\r\n\r\nUnder most circumstances, it is legal for a business to enforce a flu shot policy. In fact, some healthcare companies have even been known to fire employees who refused to be vaccinated with the flu vaccine. While <strong>vaccine injury</strong> is rare, there are well documented cases of severe and adverse effects in some people (see the Muller Brazil blog); the main reason an employee may object to injecting a live weakened virus into their system. Unfortunately for those employees who have a fear of needles or other aversion to vaccines, an employer can still require a flu vaccine in many cases.\r\n\r\nIn some situations, getting the flu vaccine is a required precondition of employment. In other situations, it might be within the confines of the law to fire an employee for violating a company’s flu shot policy due to the fact they are an at-will employee; this means they can be terminated for any reason or no reason. Many employers simply encourage employees to receive the shot by paying for the vaccine and having a medical provider come to their location to administer the shot, making it convenient for all.\r\n\r\nWhat about employees who make the legitimate argument that a mandated flu shot violates their privacy rights to exercise control over their body? Their argument is valid and they can refuse the vaccine, however this does not protect their right to work for employers wanting a workforce that is vaccinated. A worker that is not an at-will employee may have the right to refuse the flu vaccine and yet still keep their job, especially if they are a member of a union with specific employment agreements in place that enumerate specific reasons an employee may be terminated.\r\n\r\nIf you or a family member were adversely affected by the flu vaccine, and are wondering if you may have a claim, it is wise to take advantage of the free consultation offered by the skilled <strong>vaccine injury lawyers at Muller Brazil, LLP</strong>.\r\n\r\nContact <strong>Muller Brazil</strong> for a free consultation with an experienced Vaccine Injury Attorney.  Only a very small percentage of lawyers throughout the country are licensed to practice in the Federal Vaccine Court.  Muller Brazil has two attorneys licensed for Federal Vaccine practice.  In addition, you never pay legal fees to be represented by Muller Brazil for a vaccine lawsuit.  Our legal fees are paid by the government.  Contact Muller Brazil today.','Can Your Employer Force You To Get A Flu Shot?','','publish','open','open','','can-you-employer-force-you-to-get-a-flu-shot','','','2013-07-16 01:38:06','2013-07-16 01:38:06','',0,'http://myvaccineattorney.com/blog/?p=89',0,'post','',0);
