e the vaccine, however this does not protect their right to work for employers wanting a workforce that is vaccinated. A worker that is not an at-will employee may have the right to refuse the flu vaccine and yet still keep their job, especially if they are a member of a union with specific employment agreements in place that enumerate specific reasons an employee may be terminated.\r\n\r\nIf you or a family member were adversely affected by the flu vaccine, and are wondering if you may have a claim, it is wise to take advantage of the free consultation offered by the skilled <strong>vaccine injury lawyers at Muller Brazil, LLP</strong>.\r\n\r\nContact <strong>Muller Brazil</strong> for a free consultation with an experienced Vaccine Injury Attorney.  Only a very small percentage of lawyers throughout the country are licensed to practice in the Federal Vaccine Court.  Muller Brazil has two attorneys licensed for Federal Vaccine practice.  In addition, you never pay legal fees to be represented by Muller Brazil for a vaccine lawsuit.  Our legal fees are paid by the government.  Contact Muller Brazil today.','Can Your Employer Force You To Get A Flu Shot?','','inherit','open','open','','89-revision-v1','','','2013-05-07 19:34:12','2013-05-07 19:34:12','',89,'http://myvaccineattorney.com/blog/archives/109',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (110,1,'2013-04-16 18:09:27','2013-04-16 18:09:27','The Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (VAERS) is a program created and administered by the Center for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and the Food and Drug Administration (FDA).  VAERS is a program used to track adverse reactions to vaccines.  VAERS allows the public to see this information about vaccine-related injuries and reactions.\r\n\r\nThe National Childhood Vaccine Injury Act (NCVIA) of 1986 requires vaccine manufacturers and healthcare providers to report any adverse reactions to vaccines.  However, anyone can file a VAERS report, including someone who receives a vaccine and has an adverse reaction.\r\n\r\nWe recommend that if you or your children have suffered an adverse reaction to a vaccine that you do file a VAERS Report.  These reports help the Department of Health and Human Services and the Center for Disease Control and Prevention to monitor illness and injury caused by vaccines, and prevent such adverse vaccine reactions in the future.  All VAERS reports are confidential, and all individual identifiers are removed from the data posted on the VAERS website.\r\n\r\nIf you wish to report an adverse event to a vaccine to VAERS, there are three ways to do so:\r\n\r\nOnline – Proceed to this link and follow the directions:  <a href=\"https://vaers.hhs.gov/esub/step1\">https://vaers.hhs.gov/esub/step1</a>\r\n\r\nFax – Download the VAERS Form from vaers.hhs.gov.  Complete the form and fax to (877) 721-0366.\r\n\r\nMail – Download the VAERS form from vaers.hhs.gov.  Mail the completed form to:\r\n\r\nVAERS\r\n\r\nPO Box 1100\r\n\r\nRockville, MD 20849-1100.\r\n\r\nFor more information regarding VAERS, please see their website at <a href=\"http://vaers.hhs.gov/index\">http://vaers.hhs.gov/index</a>.  For more information regarding vaccine injury claims, please contact the law firm of Muller Brazil LLP for a free consultation.','Reporting Adverse Vaccine Reactions ','','inherit','open','open','','87-revision','','','2013-04-16 18:09:27','2013-04-16 18:09:27','',87,'http://myvaccineattorney.com/blog/archives/110',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (111,1,'2013-04-07 23:44:49','2013-04-07 23:44:49','The Federal Vaccine Injury Compensation Program has awarded millions of dollars to a child with autism for \"pain and suffering\" and lifelong care of their injuries, which together could cost tens of millions of dollars.\r\n\r\nIn a case involving 10-year-old Ryan Mojabi, the parents allege that vaccinations received from 2003-2005, and more specifically, measles-mumps-rubella (MMR) vaccinations, caused a severe and debilitating injury to his brain, described as Autism Spectrum Disorder (\'ASD\').\r\n\r\nThey also claimed that as a cumulative result of each vaccination between March 25, 2003 and February 22, 2005 Ryan suffered neuroimmunologically mediated dysfunctions in the form of asthma and ASD.\r\n\r\nIn vaccine court, the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services agreed that \"Ryan suffered a Table injury under the Vaccine Act -- namely, an encephalitis within five to fifteen days following receipt,\" of MMR, records show. \"This case is appropriate for compensation.\"\r\n\r\nWhether HHS agreed with Ryan\'s parents that his vaccine-induced brain disease led to ASD is unknown. The concession document is under seal.\r\n\r\nIn December 2003, when Ryan was nearly two, he received his first MMR and hepatitis B vaccines before his family left for an extended trip overseas. That day, his mother testified, Ryan began shaking with uncontrollable tremors and \"was really uncomfortable, he didn\'t feel well at all.\"\r\n\r\nThe nurse at Ryan\'s pediatrician said the symptoms were pretty normal after the vaccination, and prescribed Tylenol. The next day, Ryan began crying. The family considered postponing their holiday, but that wasn\'t feasible. The doctor\'s office said it was fine to travel. Prior to leaving, Ryan\'s mother said, the boy had difficulty breathing and was without energy and sleepy. He could no longer hold his head up, something he could do prior to the vaccinations. At the airport, Ryan began screaming, she recalled. \"He was just opening and closing his eyes so hard, he was pulling my hair.\"\r\n\r\nIn early January, while still abroad, Ryan was rushed to the hospital with vomiting, high fever and red spots covering his body,  the attending physician said. Ryan was diagnosed with \"febrile convulsion, probably related to MMR.\" The next day, another doctor diagnosed him with \"high fever, skin rash, tremors, and lethargy,\" which were \"most likely due to an adverse reaction to multiple vaccines he received earlier.\" Two days later, Ryan returned to the hospital with a persistent fever of 104 or more.\r\n\r\nRyan\'s parents testified that, upon returning home, they expressed worry to their pediatrician about behavioral problems, non-responsiveness and language loss, which later produced an ASD diagnosis.\r\n\r\nAt trial, however, the government argued powerfully that written medical records, and the recollections of Ryan\'s doctor, were inconsistent with his parents\' testimony. If Ryan had truly suffered an MMR encephalopathy, for example, his family would never have taken him overseas. And his parents\' complaints of ASD symptoms were raised a full year after returning from abroad, they alleged. It looked like the family had a weak case.\r\n\r\nBut then something changed.\r\n\r\nIn October, 2010, Ryan\'s attorney filed four new exhibits (under seal) and proposed amending the court\'s \"findings of fact.\" In January and May of 2011, several more exhibits were filed, along with a motion to further supplement the findings of fact.\r\n\r\nAward details were finally announced: A lump sum of $969,474.91, to cover \"lost future earnings ($648,132.74), pain and suffering ($202,040.17), and life care expenses for Year One ($119,302.00),\" plus $20,000 for past expenses.\r\n\r\nAnother undisclosed sum, several millions more, will be invested in annuities to cover yearly costs for life, which could total $10 million or more, not accounting for inflation. Nearly $80,000 was earmarked for ABA in the first two years.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Federal Vaccine Court Awards Millions to A Child With Autism','','inherit','open','open','','84-revision-2','','','2013-04-07 23:44:49','2013-04-07 23:44:49','',84,'http://myvaccineattorney.com/blog/archives/111',0,'revision','',0);
